Believed to be the worldâ€™s largest stockpile of seized ivory, Tanzania have ignored pressure as other African countries torch illegal ivory as a symbolic step towards saving elephants.

The Minister for Natural Resources and Tourism, Prof. Jumanne Maghembe, told US ambassador Mark Childress that the country had no plans whatsoever to destroy more than 34,000 tusks weighing roughly 125 tons stored in a closely-guarded ware<span class="text_exposed_show">house at the ministry headquarters in Dar es Salaam.</span>
<div class="text_exposed_show">

Destroying illegal ivory deters people from buying ivory products and is the most effective way to remove it completely from the black market. Kenya will be destroying 120 tons of illegal ivory on 30th April to represent their steadfast support to ending the trade.

